Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Dice @tomato{1}. Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1}.

Heat @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites and half the @Tex-Mex paste{1%unit} (all for 4) and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir in @jasmine rice{1/2%cup} and 3/4 cup water (1 1⁄2 cups for 4); bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 4.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with half the @fajita spice blend{1%tablespoon} (all for 4 servings) and @salt{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add chicken and sear, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. Transfer to a #cutting board{}; tent with #foil{} to keep warm. (Skip roasting chicken!)

> Swap in chicken* for pork.

Fluff rice with a fork; stir in tomato and chickpeas. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon} and scallion greens. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Thinly slice chicken crosswise.

Divide rice between shallow #bowls{}; top with chicken. Drizzle crema over chicken and serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.